<h2>Motivation</h2>
<p>Imagine a funnel of young software developers, oriented by skill level. At
the top of the funnel, noobs come in with no programming experience. Over the past few years,
the number of teach-kids-to-code efforts has exploded&mdash;and that's awesome! More kids (and adults)
should be coding! As they progress,
they'll find many programs/websites/classes along the way to help them gain skills.
</p>
<div style="text-align: center; margin-top: .5em; margin-bottom: .5em"><img src="/images/funnel.png" style="width: 60%;"/></div>
<p>At the other end of the funnel, highly skilled young people can land internships at
  startups, or even big companies. For example, Facebook's hired a few, high-profile
  high school graduates recently.
</p>

<p>The problem is, there are few programs help developers bridge the gap between knowing how to code,
  and knowing how to code well, from being a hacker who can cobble together an app after much
  Googling, to an engineer, who can plan and craft a readable, scalable, production-ready application.
</p>

<p>That's where Afterburner comes in: we pair talented young app developers with
  mentors from industry to coach them on the skills they need to build high-quality apps.
</p>

<h2>The Program</h2>

<p>
  Afterburner is a 12-week program designed to teach talented high school developers
about building well-crafted mobile apps, focusing on skills like...
</p>
<ul>
  <li>Software architecture</li>
  <li>Code readability and maintainability</li>
  <li>Scalability</li>
  <li>Testing</li>
</ul>

<p>Throughout the program, cadets work on a project of their own choosing and
  an experienced mobile developer coaches them and reviews their code. Currently,
  Afterburner is focused on iOS development skills, but may expand to Android
  in the future.
</p>

